Containers are ephemeralâ€”data vanishes when a container stops. Thatâ€™s where volumes come in.
âœ… Persist data across container restarts
âœ… Share data between containers
âœ… Useful for databases, logs, configs

# Create a volume
docker volume create mydata

# Use it in a container
docker run -v mydata:/app/data myapp

ğŸ”¸ ğ——ğ—¼ğ—°ğ—¸ğ—²ğ—¿ ğ—¡ğ—²ğ˜ğ˜„ğ—¼ğ—¿ğ—¸ğ—¶ğ—»ğ—´ ğ—•ğ—®ğ˜€ğ—¶ğ—°ğ˜€
Containers need to talkâ€”to each other, and to the world. Docker provides built-in networks:

bridge (default): Good for single-host setups

host: Container shares host network

none: Isolated network

custom bridge: Better control over DNS and isolation

# Create a user-defined bridge network
docker network create mynet

# Connect containers to it
docker run -d --name app1 --network mynet nginx
docker run -d --name app2 --network mynet alpine ping app1
